                            @{b}@{u}@{fg highlight}SHORT INTRODUCTION@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

@{b}@{u}Disclaimer:@{ub}@{uu} Use or don't use this program, it's your decision. I will be not responsible for any damage! I just can tell you, that I have tested the program on my machine for many months and there was no problem, but I only guarantee the usage of diskspace. Short: @{b}FREEWARE@{ub}

Why a short introduction: Sorry but my english is as worse as (I can't tell you that here and now!) and working in the night is not the thing of mine. So there is only a short explanation in english.

@{b}@{u}Why this program exists:@{ub}@{uu} It's a hard job to include pictures in LaTeX. Specialhost (which came with PasTeX) can do many very wonderful things, but YOU have to tell what it should do. So you can use a calculator and much time. So therefore I considered to write this program to help me and my friends to include pictures with PasTeX and specialhost. If you don't use this Programs (it's also FREEWARE!) you can stop at this point!

@{b}@{u}Installation:@{ub}@{uu} Put TeXpic in any directory (but tex:bin seems to be the best one) in your path and make a directory tex:texpic. That's all.

@{b}@{u}Usage:@{ub}@{uu} The program can only be run from the Cli. If the program detects an inputerror it will show a little help, if you type "TeXpic ?" it will show a bigger help.  The first argument is the name with the current path to the picture; the program truncs the path, so don't worry about it at this time. The second argument is the width of the picture in cm (only the number) or the density of your printer in DPI  (number with trailing d). The third optional argument is the path (with trailing / or :) of the outputfile; if you don't specify the outputpath, the outputfile will be placed in the current directory.

**************************** Example *****************************************

So there are two ways to your aim: If you want a picture named foo with a width of 10cm included, you type:

TeXpic foo 10

The output will be named "foo.tex".

If you want a picture named foo2 (for example a dithered picture) printed 1:1 on your printer with 300dpi you will type:

TeXpic foo2 300d

**************************** Example *****************************************

Last you will have to copy your picture in the directory tex:texpic, because that's the path used in the outputfile. 

**************************** Tips ********************************************

* Don't use picturenames with extensions in this version. The program will produce an outputfile like foo.gif.tex. That might confuse TeX!

* Don't name your picture with an extension .tex, because the outputfile will be named .tex.tex and that confuses TeX!

* Don't name your picture with letters, that confuse TeX like ö,ä,ß,í and so on!

* The Outfile sets the colormode to bw (black and white). If you want to change this, you will have to edit this in the Outputfile per hand.

**************************** Tips ********************************************

Now it's time to include the picture in your LaTeX-source. You have only to type "\\input {Picturename}" in the file on the right place and that's all. If you want to see the picture, make sure specialhost ist running!

Style: I have included a style (LaTeX 2.09 but I think also for LaTeX2e) that makes some things easier for you. Look in the style with your editor for a @{"short description" link "mypic.sty/main" 0}. If you have included this style in your document, you can very easy put pictures in your LaTeX-documents by typing only one line by hand. For example:

**************************** Example *****************************************

{include the style}

....

\\bPic{foo}{This is my first picture in LaTeX}{foo1}

Now you have the picture placed in a floating, with the above text as caption and you can reference it like 

\\ref{foo1} on page \\pageref{foo1}

**************************** Example *****************************************

It can't be easier!

